metadata.name: Miniscapes #353
metadata.description:
Miniscapes merges generative code (Rich's bit) with meticulously designed scenes and elements (Rick's bit), to create minimalist landscapes intended to charm, delight, and surprise.

Our aim was to convey as much as possible with as little as possible by using simple shapes and lines to represent a wide variety of natural landscapes.

We hope that you find as much joy in owning a Miniscape as we did in creating them.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to save the current image
- Press [p] to pause an animated output
- Press [r] to reset an animated output (this will also pause)

metadata.name: TENDER Pass #995
metadata.description:
Tender is a curatorial platform and community that helps bring incredible works of generative art to discerning collectors.

Holding a TENDER Pass enables enriched benefits and experiences within the Tender ecosystem. metadata.name: Rooted #23
metadata.description:
"Rooted" is part of the live minting experience at Non Fungible Conference Lisbon, June 7-8, 2023.

—

Home is more than where we live, it is where we belong. It is where we are safe. Home does not belong to us, we belong to it. As I stand in wildflower meadows and watch the sun cross mountain peaks, I am home.

—

This project is a collaboration between artist, algorithm, and collector. The minters’ wallet address and fx(params) are used in place of a transaction hash for seeding random values, resulting in a WYSIWYG minting experience.

metadata.name: Sixty# #256
metadata.description:
This idea was born from recent discussion on generative art and the path the medium is finding for itself. The project aims to take aesthetic concepts from sci fi graphic novels and blend them with generative systems of abstraction. 

The debate is between using previously established art forms to influence this new medium, or using a new medium to meticulously reproduce a previous medium. I believe there’s room to explore the full spectrum, and I am attempting to find the midpoint that fits my work and brings me the most happiness.

The title describes the eventual aesthetic objective, which is to create a piece which might look like a splash page a colorist alone has been given the freedom to design and explore their own specialty. It explores centralized polar compositions, vibrant colors, plus lots and lots of movement. 60# paper is a standard weight for printing of comic books and graphic novels.

Press ’s’ in live view to save a .png

Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: Uninhabitable #310
metadata.description:
Uninhabitable is a generative system built only from ellipses. The process of playing with different geometric and trigonometric disruptions gives rise to four different compositions which seek to evoque living constructions and environments. Besides the shape itself and its related distortion, the stroke weight of the lines plays a meaningful role in the piece. Following a discrete range [0.01,0.1,1] the weight reveals the process allowing the viewer to realize the trace of the huge amount of lines in each piece. This back and forth between scales and context is, while kind of stripping the code, part of my continuing interest on understanding the -usually- crazy paths of machines' way of thinking.

Press "h" to see it and high resolution and refresh to get back to the initial state. Press "h" to save it.

Uninhabitable is an original work by Iskra Velitchkova. 2021.

metadata.name: Marsborne #4
metadata.description:
This artwork is a digital collage and image compositing that utilizes a combination of computer-generated imagery (CGI) and artificial intelligence.
The layering and random placement of elements create an image that is unique and divergent from what a human artist might create.

The final composition is achieved through the use of a custom-written javascript program that I wrote in pure javascript, which allows for the layers to be placed together randomly

========
If you see this NFT on OBJKT this is a generative art minted on FXhash.com
========

Resolution : 2400 x 2400

Twitter : @AITezoart
@ 2023

metadata.name: tezzolation #12
metadata.description:
tezzolation is a mashup of tez, tessellation, and desolation.

Textural elements are tessellated in isometric geometry with reflections and rotations by multiples of 30 degrees. Some elements are generated on the fly (borrowing drawing tech from Buragh) and others are pre-generated by AI algorithms. 
Some tessellations are clean, others are fractured. All exhibit desolation depicted by vertical fading.

Press "s" to save as a 4096x3072 pixel png image

metadata.name: Exoplanets in texture #4
metadata.description:
By having exotic molecular compositions and suitable life conditions, habitability chances increase and different textures take place.

These planets can be divided into 4 main climate zones. A dry one, a wet one, a vegetative one and one that is a mix of all of the above.

Drag to ROTATE the planet horizontally.
Scroll or pinch to ZOOM in.

There is a 50% chance of getting a mixed planet, and 1/6 to get any of the others.
All planets have one dominating texture, which is generated from a total of 12.
Mountains, trees, crystals and other subtle decorations are randomly populated.
With each planet type comes a different audio theme.

@computeremotions - 2022-09-24

metadata.name: Caught in the maelstrom #116
metadata.description:
An ever-growing vortex consisting of lots of different mesh lines that move in unison.

Clicking the canvas will trigger a boost in speed and line size, and produce a random chord by the main synth.

Holding down your pointer will reverse the vortex and play an additional synth on release. Double tapping will have the same effect audio-wise.

This is part of the celebration of fxhash turning 1. That’s why there are 365 editions, and 50% of all primary sales will be donated evenly between “Processing Foundation” and “Three.js”. 20% of all royalties are given back to the minter.

Here are some stats for you:

About 1/10 will render the lines in wireframes.
There are 2 different synth pitches distributed evenly.
10% will have one single line color, instead of 3 primary ones.
In rough measures, every 4th will have an irregular wiggle motion flow instead of a circular one.

In addition to all of the above, there can be different values in regards to line counts, line lengths, line widths, speeds, width grows, radius increments, angle increments, z-index increments, background colors, border colors, and so on.

#fxhashturnsone

@computeremotions - 2022-11-13

metadata.name: Puzzled Picture #93
metadata.description:
This work is composed of a combination of grids with line patterns, like my previous work "Infinite Animation" (Project #15745).  However, whereas the previous work was characterized by simplicity and regularity, this one is much more chaotic.

First, while in the previous work the grids were fixed at 3 x 3, in this work there are variations from 5 x 5 to 20 x 20. 
And in this work, it is YOU who rotates the grid. Clicking on a grid rotates it 90 degrees and changes the image. If you have difficulty locating the grid, press the "g" key on the keyboard to display a guide (for touch devices, long press to show/hide the guide).
If you get tired of clicking, you can ask your computer to help you. You can toggle the animation mode with the "a" key on the keyboard (for touch devices, swipe up to turn on the mode, swipe down to turn it off). In animation mode, the computer rotates a random grid at regular intervals. (The surrounding frame turns green in animation mode.)

The fun of generative art lies in finding value, or to stretch the point a bit, destiny, in the random coincidences created by computers. Therefore, it is not aesthetically pleasing to artificially modify the derived result later. However, dynamism is also a characteristic of digital art. The fluidity of the results is probably one of its interesting features. I experimented with it in my previous work, "Abstract Calligraphy"(Project #15384), and have done it more characteristically in this project.

This picture is like a puzzle game, but there is no correct answer. No, there may be a correct answer. It depends on your aesthetic sense. Let's enjoy collaborating with the computer!
